Data Overview¶

PISA is the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD)'s Programme for International Student Assessment. PISA measures 15-year-olds’ ability to use their reading, mathematics and science knowledge and skills to meet real-life challenges. For this analysis, I focused on resources, mindsets and math outcomes.

WOW! 636 columns! Using the PISA dictionary, I am going to narrow that down by coming up with some questions. I am going to focus on mathematics, and study the relationship between resources, societal norms, mindset, and outcomes.

STIDSTD Student ID

Quality¶

  • Plausible values dtype is object; should be float
  • ST115Q01, skipped classes within day, dtype is object; should be int
  • ST08Q01, tardies; ST09Q01, absences; ST26Q01, desk ownership; ST26Q02, room ownership; ST26Q06, internet access; ST27Q01, cell phones; ST27Q02, TVs; ST27Q03, PCs; ST27Q05, bathrooms; ST28Q01, books; ST35Q02, friends' work ethic in math; ST35Q04, parents belief in math importance; ST42Q01, worry about math difficulty; ST46Q01, math homework timely; ST46Q06, pay attention in math; ST80Q08, learn from mistakes; ST87Q03, feeling of belonging at school; ST89Q05, best effort is important; ST91Q01, effort results in success; ST93Q01, gives up easily, dtype is object; should be categorical
  • Lots of null/NaN values in the categorical response columns

Tidiness¶

  • Some United States values broken out into States
  • Student IDs are not entirely unique
  • ST01Q01: International Grade, ST03Q01: Birth - Month, ST03Q02: Birth -Year, W_FSTUWT: FINAL STUDENT WEIGHT, WVARSTRR: RANDOMIZED FINAL VARIANCE STRATUM (1-80), VAR_UNIT: RANDOMLY ASSIGNED VARIANCE UNIT, SENWGT_STU: Senate weight - sum of weight within the country is 1000, and VER_STU: Date of the database creation, do not appear to valuable to my avenue of exploration.

Plausible values, and ST115Q01, skipped classes within day, dtype is object; should be float¶

ST08Q01, tardies; ST09Q01, absences; ST26Q01, desk ownership; ST26Q02, room ownership; ST26Q06, internet access; ST27Q01, cell phones; ST27Q02, TVs; ST27Q03, PCs; ST27Q05, bathrooms; ST28Q01, books; ST35Q02, friends' work ethic in math; ST35Q04, parents belief in math importance; ST42Q01, worry about math difficulty; ST46Q01, math homework timely; ST46Q06, pay attention in math; ST80Q08, learn from mistakes; ST87Q03, feeling of belonging at school; ST89Q05, best effort is important; ST91Q01, effort results in success; ST93Q01, gives up easily, dtype is object; should be categorical¶

Define¶

Convert datatypes with .astype(float), and pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype

Code¶
In [19]:
df_clean[['ST115Q01', 'PV1MATH', 'PV2MATH', 'PV3MATH', 'PV4MATH', 'PV5MATH']] = df_clean[['ST115Q01', 'PV1MATH', 'PV2MATH', 'PV3MATH', 'PV4MATH', 'PV5MATH']].astype(float)
In [20]:
def catconv1(A,B):#A=define type, B=column to change
    cat_type1 = ['None  ', 'One or two times  ', 'Three or four times  ', 'Five or more times  ']
    A =  pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=cat_type1)
    df_clean[B] = df_clean[B].astype(A)

catconv1("tardies", "ST08Q01")
catconv1("absences", "ST09Q01")
    
def catconv2(A,B):#A=define type, B=column to change
    cat_type2 = ['None', 'One', 'Two', 'Three or more']
    A =  pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=cat_type2)
    df_clean[B] = df_clean[B].astype(A)

catconv2("cells", "ST27Q01")
catconv2("tvs", "ST27Q02")
catconv2("PCs", "ST27Q03")
catconv2("baths", "ST27Q05")

def catconv3(A,B):#A=define type, B=column to change
    cat_type3 = ['Strongly agree', 'Agree', 'Disagree', 'Strongly disagree']
    A =  pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=cat_type3)
    df_clean[B] = df_clean[B].astype(A)

catconv3("friends", "ST35Q02")
catconv3("parents", "ST35Q04")
catconv3("math_worries", "ST42Q01")
catconv3("mathHW", "ST46Q01")
catconv3("math_attns", "ST46Q06")
catconv3("belonging", "ST87Q03")
catconv3("best_efforts", "ST89Q05")
catconv3("success", "ST91Q01")

cat_type4 = ['0-10 books ', '11-25 books ', '26-100 books ', '101-200 books ', '201-500 books ', 'More than 500 books']
book_num =  pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=cat_type4)
df_clean["ST28Q01"] = df_clean["ST28Q01"].astype(book_num)

cat_type5 = ['Never or rarely', 'Sometimes', 'Often', 'Always or almost always']
learn =  pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=cat_type5)
df_clean["ST80Q08"] = df_clean["ST80Q08"].astype(learn)

cat_type6 = ['Not at all like me','Not much like me', 'Somewhat like me', 'Mostly like me', 'Very much like me']
giveup =  pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=cat_type6)
df_clean["ST93Q01"] = df_clean["ST93Q01"].astype(giveup)

Student IDs are not entirely unique¶
ST01Q01: International Grade, ST03Q01: Birth - Month, ST03Q02: Birth -Year, W_FSTUWT: FINAL STUDENT WEIGHT, WVARSTRR: RANDOMIZED FINAL VARIANCE STRATUM (1-80), VAR_UNIT: RANDOMLY ASSIGNED VARIANCE UNIT, SENWGT_STU: Senate weight - sum of weight within the country is 1000, and VER_STU: Date of the database creation, do not appear to valuable to my avenue of exploration.¶

Eliminate these columns using .drop(). Give remaining columns more meaningful names with .rename().

NOTE FROM PISA TECHNICAL GUIDE

It cannot be emphasised too strongly that the plausible values are not a substitute for test scores for individuals. Plausible values incorporate responses to test items and information about the background of responses; therefore, they cannot be used to compare individuals.

https://www.oecd.org/pisa/sitedocument/PISA-2015-Technical-Report-Chapter-9-Scaling-PISA-Data.pdf

cat_type7 = ['No', 'Yes']

def propbar(A,B):
    cat2_order = B #category type
    artists = [] # for storing references to plot elements
    baselines = np.zeros(len(labels))
    cat1_counts = df_clean['CNT'].value_counts()
    
    # for each second-variable category:
    for i in range(len(cat2_order)):
        # isolate the counts of the first category,
        cat2 = cat2_order[i]
        inner_counts = df_clean[df_clean[A] == cat2]['CNT'].value_counts()
        inner_props = inner_counts / cat1_counts
        # then plot those counts on top of the accumulated baseline
        bars = plt.bar(x = np.arange(len(labels)),
                       height = inner_props[labels],
                       bottom = baselines)
        artists.append(bars)
        baselines += inner_props[labels]
        
        plt.xticks(np.arange(len(labels)), labels)
        plt.legend(reversed(artists), reversed(cat2_order), framealpha = 1,
                   bbox_to_anchor = (1, 0.5), loc = 6)
        plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right');
        
#raw count bar graph defined

def multipropplot(A,B): #variable A, category type B
    PVLEVEL_counts = (df1.groupby(['PV_LEVEL'])[A]
                                           .value_counts(normalize=True)
                                           .rename('percentage')
                                           .mul(100)
                                           .reset_index()
                                           .sort_values(A))
    category =  pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=B)

#define categories and plotting
cat_type1 = ['None  ', 'One or two times  ', 'Three or four times  ', 'Five or more times  ']
cat_type2 = ['None', 'One', 'Two', 'Three or more']
cat_type3 = ['Strongly agree', 'Agree', 'Disagree', 'Strongly disagree']
cat_type4 = ['0-10 books ', '11-25 books ', '26-100 books ', '101-200 books ', '201-500 books ', 'More than 500 books']
cat_type5 = ['Never or rarely', 'Sometimes', 'Often', 'Always or almost always']
cat_type6 = ['Not at all like me','Not much like me', 'Somewhat like me', 'Mostly like me', 'Very much like me']

def multipropplot_BRVT(A,B,C): #variable, categorical type, title
    PVLEVEL_counts = (df1_BRVT.groupby(['CNT', 'PV_LEVEL'])[A]
                                           .value_counts(normalize=True)
                                           .rename('percentage')
                                           .mul(100)
                                           .reset_index()
                                           .sort_values(A))
    category =  pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=B)
    PVLEVEL_counts[A] = PVLEVEL_counts[A].astype(category)
    p = sb.catplot(x="percentage", y=A, hue='PV_LEVEL', col='CNT', palette="Blues_d", data=PVLEVEL_counts.sort_values('CNT'), kind="bar", alpha=0.8)
    p.set(ylabel="Response")
    plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.9)
    p.fig.suptitle(C)
    
multipropplot_BRVT("ABSENT", cat_type1, "Attendance")

We confirm again that the mojority of students have fewer than three absences.

In [117]:
multipropplot_BRVT("BOOKS", cat_type4, "How Many Books at Home");

Both Vietnamese and Brazilian students have fewer books in general, with 26-100 books being the threshold for the highest proportion of HI scoring students. It seems much less significant for Vietnamese students, where the proportion of LO scoring students even outpaces other groups for more than 500 books.

There isn't significantly more negative mindset in the Brazilian subset; if anything, they showed higher proportions of positive mindsets than the higher scoring Vietnamese students, but there are some interesting differences in resource access. Vietnamese students seemed to have less access to resources than Brazilians. The only measurable where the Vietnamese students clearly outpaced the Brazilians was desk ownership.

Conclusion¶

Viewing the dataset as a whole, and within nations, there were key insights into the correlations between mindset, access, and math PV outcomes. My findings revealed desks, PCs, internet access, and books in the home all positively impact the distritution of PV. As do beliefs about the importance of effort, its relationship to success, perseverance, and perception of parental belief in math importance.

While we could see correlations within the nations, there were not any clear patterns uncovered to explain why Vietnamese students' PV was so much greater than Brazilian students' PV. Perhaps there is a compounding generational factor that isn't sufficiently measured by the current PISA methodology.
